We learn from the New York papers that four vessels, within sight of each other, are ashore on Squam Beach; one ship, (the Cornelius Grinnell, from London,) two barques, one of them new, from the Eastward, and a brig. The Cornelius Grinnell will be a total loss.-- Her back is broken, and all her masts cut away. The passengers, numbering three hundred, wre landed. She is valued at $80,000, and insured.

Schr. Arctic, Wilson, hnce, at New York, 30 h, reports 15th instant, off Smith's Island, Schr. Columbia, 14 days from Norfolk, bound to New York, returning to Norfolk (since arrived at Norfolk.) The C. on th 7th instant, was off the Highlands in the NE gale and snow storm; had her sails all blown to pieces; lost all their water casks, and had been four days without water. Captain Wilson supplied them with water. Capt. W. reports eight fore and aft schooners ashore between Chicoteague and Squam beach.

The Schr. Kate Stewart, from this port, for Philadelphia, has been cut through by the ice, and sunk at the mouth of Back Creek

Ship Geo. A. Hopley from this port at Liverpool, experienced a heavy gale. Dec. 19, was struck by a sea, which washed over man overboard. Dec. 20, encountered a hurricane, during which the long boat was smashed to pieces, bulwarks broken, fortopgallantmast and mainsail were lost, and she also received other damage. Experienced WNW, and WSW winds all the passage.

Schr. Kate Stuart, Dennis, from this port, bound for Philadelphia, was cut through by the ice, on Saturday, 22d ult., near the head of the Chesapeake Bay. The Captain finding that she was fast sinking, ran her ashore, where she filled with water. At low tide she lies in six feet water. Capt. D. went to Baltimore to procure lighters, and thinks he will get her off without much damage or expense. Her cargo, which consists principally of feed, will be damaged. The vessel is insured in Philadelphia.

Loss of Brig. Wheeler -- The brig Wheeler, Captain Brown, from Baltimore for Boston, with a cargo of coal, was struck by a heavy squall at 2 P.M., on Monday, 4th instant, near Smith's Point light, which hove her down on her beam ends, and she soon after filled and sunk in nine fathoms water. Fortunately for the crew, the boat was not lashed to the deck, and on its floating off they succeeded in getting into it, and pulled away to the light boat, but meeting the schooner John Spedden, bound up, were taken on board and brought to this port. The captain says he saw the squall coming on, and succeeded in taking in all the light sails, and main sail, and was in that trim when struck by the N. W. squall. The crew saved nothing. -- BALTIMORE AMERICAN.

Ship Persian, ashore on Fire Ireland, will become a total wreck: she lies broadside on to the beach, the sea making a complete breach over her. Her decks are broken in, and part of the cargo is strewn for miles along the beach: about 500 packages of goods, and 300 baskets Champagne Wine have been saved -- all damaged. A party has contracted to save whatever materials he can of the ship on the part of the underwriters of Baltimore, for 50 per cent. She was owned by Messrs. Kirkland, Chase & Co., and insured in Baltimore, for $20,000.

Captain Hall, of the Schr. Enoch French, reports having passed on the 1st instant, southeast from Cape Henlopen, about 30 miles, a wrecked vessel on her beam ends, waterlogged, with coppered bottom; saw on the stern, the letters Osca, could not see the other part of her name, being sunk in the water. Supposed her to be a Brig of about 200 to 250 tons, with spars alongside, and appeared to have been run down -- no person on board. Next day, off Hog Island, passed the wreck of another vessel about 200 tons, waterlogged and dismasted, could not make out her name, she had white rails, black bulwarks, and wide white streak.

Steam propeller Albany, Butler, New York, bound to Trangier's Sound, in distress, put in for repairs. On 17th, 3 miles E. of Smith's island, boiler gave out and steamer was disabled, towed in and laid at anchor in Hampton Roads, in storm and went ashore at Old Point, after getting off was carried by ice of Horse Shoe.

Steamer Caledonia, Layfield, from Hampton Roads, having in tow bark Homer.          The Caledonia sailed from New York, Friday night, for the purpose of relieving vessels in distress, and arrived in the Roads Sunday.        Has supplied several vessels with provisions, and rendered great services. Assisted in relieving the ship Sultan; got her off; both were afterwards driven ashore by ice, in consequence of accidentally getting hawser in wheel.       The Caledonia left last evening, towing down a schr. for lightening the Sultan. Mate of SUltan had his thigh broken Tuesday night, by the parting of hawser, and brought up yesterday.

Brig. Homer, Gardner, from Hampton Roads, yesterday towed up by steamer Caledonia. Left Malaga on the 26th November and Gibraltar on the 2d of December bound to New York, arrived in the Capes 25th, having experienced exceedingly heavy weather. Top sails split into ribbons; vessel in leaking condition; started partners to foremast, stove boats sprung foretopmast, racked foretops, strained water-ways badly. Put in for repairs to Alex. Bell & Son.

Bark Richmond, from York River, Va., for Boston, put into Holmes' Hole 22d inst., having, on the night of 18th inst., Black Island, W. 10 miles been in contact ith brig Henrico, Fiske, from Para, 27th ult., of and for Salem, and lost jibboom foreyard, cutwater, rail broker, and bulwarks stove on the larboard side; damage to the Henrico unknown. Mr. E. P. Baily, of Salem, a passenger on the Henrico, got on board of the Richmond, at the time of the collision, and was taken to Holmes' Hole. Reports the Henrico to have been struck amidships.

WILMINGTON, N.C., Sept. 16 -- G. W. Davis, Esq., consignee of schr. New Republic, (before reported ashore near New Topsail Inlet,) returned to town last night, and reports that on yesterday about two-thirds of the cargo was taken out, the larger portion of which is in good condition; and was carried over the beach to two small vessels inside, which will be brought to town without delay. More force had been sent to the wreck, and it is supposed that the balance will be gotten out to-day in a damaged state. -- Vessel a total loss.

Schr. N. M. Tannor, Todd, which sailed from Charleston, 14th inst., for Richmond, Va., loaded with railroad iron, put back 17th, leaky. Monday morning a northerly gale set in, with heavy seas. Tuesday morning 11 o'clock, while reefing, sprung a leak, in lat. 35'36, lon. 72 1/2. Finding vessel making much water, kept off for Wilmington; arrived off Frying Pan Shoals at 8 o'clock P.M.; not being able to get in, bore off for Charleston -- wind blowing heavy from northeast, with a tremendous sea. Arrived off Charleston Bar and took a pilot at 7 o'clock Wednesday morning; both pumps going and fifteen inches water in the hold.

LEWES, DEL., Sept. 20.-- We had quite a storm on Saturday evening from the North. The schr. Contee, light, from New York bound to Virginia, and the fishing sloop W. Haggett, were driven ashore and their hulls consequently damaged. The schr. Will be sold to-day. The schr. Fanny Fern, from Boston for Richmond, had her sails blown away. The Captain has sent to New York for a new suit. There are about thirty vessels at harbor, which came in last evening.

BALTIMORE, Oct. 18.-- Jas. Cary Cole, agent of the New York Board of Underwriters, yesterday received information that a schooner, name and destination unknown, loaded with logwood and 300 bags of coffee, had gone ashore near Hog Island Light, in a dismasted condition. ONe-half of the coffee had been landed, and directions were sent to the Commissioner of Wrecks, Mr. Goffagan, to have it conveyed to Norfolk.

NORFOLK, April 16,-- [] The schr. Ocean Wave, Capt. Slacum, of Oxford, from this port for Petersburg, with a cargo of bricks, guano and sundry merchandize, encountered a heavy squall on the 16th inst., at 4 P.M., off Sewell's Point, and sprung mainmast, injuring sails, causing the vessel to leak so badly as to render it necessary to run her on the flats at Ferry Point, to prevent her from sinking. She will be compelled to discharge and haul up to caulk. She has two feet of water in her hold.

The schr. B. B. Bean, from Richmond, Virginia, bound to Rio de Janeiro, on the 7th ult., when in long. 77 deg. to the North of the Gulf, with wind at N.E., it commenced blowing a heavy gale. The schooner broke her bowsprit, split her sails and sprung a leak; the leak increasing, her captain was induced to bear up for Bermuda Islands, where he arrived Sept. 20th. The Bean is now in that port, and on survey it is recommended that her cargo be discharged. Her cargo consists of 2,100 barrels of flour

The ship John Milton, Harding, with guano, fm Chincha Islands, arrived in Hampton Roads on the 13th inst, (as before reported) from whence she sailed on the same day for New York, and went ashore on Montank Point L. J. on the 20th inst., during a violent gale which prevailed at the time. All her officers and crew are reported lost, eight dead bodies together with the captain's writing desk having been washed ashore. She was a fine ship, owned in New Bedford, and is a total loss.

Arrived at Balt. Feb. 20th, steamer Louisiana, Capt. Russell, fm this port. Reports at 25 minutes before 10 last night, about 5 miles below the Rappahannock light boat, came in collision with a schr., name unknown, striking her on the port side, aft the main rigging. She had changed her course and was heading across the bay at the time, expecting, no doubt, to clear the steamer. Immediately on seeing the schr., the steamer was stopped and had commenced backing when the collision occurred. All the schooner's crew got safely on board the Louisiana and were brought to this city. The vessel soon filled and sank. The Louisiana sustained no injury whatever, having struck with but little force. We were unable to obtain the name of the schr., or those of her crew which consisted of five white men. She hailed from the Delaware, and supposed bound there. The Louisiana had given her a wide birth, and had she kept on her proper course, as she was bound down the bay, the collission would have been avoided. (We have since ascertained that the Schr. sunk was the Wm. K. Parran, Charles Ogden, master, loaded with oysters.)

Ship Star of Hope, Pearsons, from Callao 107 days, has had fine weather until when in lat 23 [degrees] N, from which time they have had a succession of very heavy Westwardly and North Westwardly gales; arrived inside the Capes on the 10th, took a Pilot; at 3 P.M., and at about 8 P.M., she got ashore on Willoughby's Point, assistance has been sent to her. Reports when off Cape Horn, January 3rd, spoke Whaling Bark, D. Thompson, fm Honolulu, bd to the Falkland Islands, in lat 19 [degrees] 49' longitude 58 [degrees] 41' spoke the Baltimore Ship Bansher, fm Rio, bd to Baltimore, having sickness on board. In lat 10 [degrees] 19' long 33 [degrees] 50' Signalled, English Bark Coreasia, fm Honolulu, bd to the Falkland Islands. In lat 24 [degrees] 28' long 63 [degrees] 45' spoke Boston ship Bornia, bd to New York.

Brig Newsboy, Leckie, of Boston, from Fayall, in ballast to J. M. Smith & Bro. The Newsboy sailed from Fayall on the 6th of February, on 10th had a severe gale from westward and a heavy sea, which stove bulwarks and stancheon from gafrail to gangway --- also carried away main boom and the man at the wheel had his leg Broken -- they put back to Fayall for repairs fm whence she sailed again on the 23d February since which date they have had a succession of heavy gales from the westward

Schr. Pauline, Jones, of Newbern, N.J., sailed from Newborne on 16th Feb. for New York, with naval stores, on 2d March, during the prevalence of a heavy gale, washed part of deck load of rosin overboard, and the vessel laboring heavily -- they were compelled for the general preservation to throw over the balance of deck load -- the gale continued with unbated violence until 8th inst., on which day they lost the boat, had bulwarks stove, and sustained considerable other damage -- the vessel also sprung a leak, and the pumps becoming out of order, they on the 10th inst, hove away for the nearest port for repairs. On 11th inst., in lat 35.33, lon 70.28, were spoken by the Schr. Alma, from Antiqua bound to Norfolk. The crew of the Pauline having become completely exhausted fm excessive labor at the pumps -- they asked to be taken off, a boat was sent from the Alma and they went on board of that vessel during the night -- they had a strong breeze and the Almy lay by the Pauline until morning of 12th, when they put a crew on board the latter vessel and proceeded with her up to Norfolk, where they arrived this morning to Hardy & Bros. [probably Newberg, NC -- not NJ)

At the Poplars, in Nanjemoy Beach, on Monday night, a schooner loaded with coal blew ashore. An effort was made by the James Guy on Tuesday to get her off -- but without success. -- Since then, a portion of the cargo has been landed -- and, it is supposed she will soon be got off.

There are at this time about 200 outward bound vessels of every sort, anchored in Hampton Roads, detained there by the prevalent Eastern winds, and waiting a favorable chance to put to sea. Many of these crafts are laden with grain and other produce for Northern ports, and some of them have been thus wind-bound for nearly a fortnight past.-- Norfolk Herald, April 11th.

The Schr. Fleetwood left New York, on the 17th of February last, for Alexandria, Va. At 11 o'clock, P.M., she struck upon the bar known as Hereford outer bar, near Cape May, the wind at the time blowing heavily, and the sea rough. Finding it impossible to run my anchor with my own boat, I succeeded in landing upon an island near by, upon which is placed, by Government, a life boat, and other fixtures, to be used by vessels in distress, but could find no one in whose charge these things were placed I broke open the house, obtained the life boat, and happily succeeded in getting the vessel off without damage. Could I not have got possession of this life boat, my vessel must have been inevitably lost, as it was utterly impossible to run the anchor with the vessel's boat. Government is entitled to a great deal of credit for placing the means of saving life and property in this place; but it certainly can be rendered of very little use, if, as at present, all these articles are to be locked up, and the key in possession of a man at a distance of 8 miles from them. Government pays a salary of $200, I think, to have these things taken care of; but they would render them much more efficient by placing them in the hands of some person to be upon the spot when they are required. EPHRIAM BURR.
